\cf2 \cb3 Stanza xvii., line 2.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa132\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 "Few towns have contributed more largely to the reputation of Roman literature, or have been more fertile in the production of genius, taste and knowledge, than Verona. Catullus and Macer, supposed to be introduced by Virgil into his Eclogues, under the pastoral name of Mopsus; Cornelius Nepos and Pomponius Secundus; Vitruvius and Pliny the Elder, form a constellation of luminaries of the first magnitude, and shed a distinguishing lustre on the place of their birth and early education."-
\f1\i Eustace's Classical 
\f0\i0 Tour, Vol. I. Chap. 
\f1\i II
\f0\i0 .\cb1 \
